# Pre-commit security review

Whenever the user asks to **commit**, **amend**, or you are about to run `git commit`:

## 1. Run the security-reviewer subagent first

- Delegate to the **`security-reviewer`** subagent (`.cursor/agents/security-reviewer.md`).
- Use the **Task** tool with `subagent_type: "security-reviewer"` when available.
- Otherwise follow that agent’s workflow yourself: `git status`, `git diff` (staged + unstaged), and `git diff main...HEAD` (or the repo default branch) for branch context.
- Review **only changes that would be included in the commit** (staged files; include unstaged only if the user intends to commit everything).

## 2. Report a short summary to the user

Always post before committing:

```markdown
## Security review (pre-commit)

**Recommendation:** approve | approve with fixes | **block**

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| Critical | N |
| High     | N |
| Medium   | N |
| Low      | N |

### Findings (brief)
- [Critical/High] Title — file:line — one-line risk
- …

### Residual risks (if any)
- …
```

## 3. Gate the commit on Critical issues

- **If any Critical finding exists:** do **not** run `git commit`. Warn clearly:

  > **Commit blocked:** Critical security issue(s) must be fixed before committing. Say when fixed and I will re-run the security review.

- Offer concrete fixes from the review. Re-run security-reviewer after fixes before committing.

- **If no Critical issues:** you may proceed with the commit. Still mention High/Medium items briefly if present.

- **User override:** Only commit with open Critical issues if the user **explicitly** says to skip security fixes (e.g. “commit anyway”); note the override in your reply.

## 4. LLM / API key changes

If the commit touches triage, `llmKey`, `api/triage`, `src/triage.js`, or session persistence, also verify the **LLM / API key checklist** in `security-reviewer.md`.

## 5. Do not skip

- Do not commit first and review later.
- Do not treat this as optional when the user rule or commit request is active.
